---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'cerberus-fossae');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Cerberus Fossae location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Cerberus Fossae - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-red-900 to-orange-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Mars Express view of Cerberus Fossae's dramatic fracture system
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">ESA/DLR/FU Berlin</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Cerberus Fossae represents one of Mars' most geologically active regions, 
          consisting of a series of parallel fractures extending over 1,200 kilometers 
          across the Elysium Planitia. This dramatic fissure system has emerged as 
          the primary source of marsquakes detected by NASA's InSight mission, 
          challenging our understanding of Mars as a geologically dormant world.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The fossae (Latin for "trenches") are relatively young geological features, 
          formed within the last few million years through tectonic activity driven 
          by volcanic processes beneath the surface. These parallel fractures represent 
          active extension of the Martian crust, with some segments showing evidence 
          of recent lava flows and pyroclastic deposits.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Recent discoveries from InSight's seismometer have revealed that over 90% 
          of detected marsquakes originate from this region, suggesting ongoing 
          magmatic activity at depths of 30-50 kilometers. This makes Cerberus Fossae 
          a cornerstone location for understanding Mars' current geological processes 
          and potential for continued volcanic activity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Length:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">1,200+ km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">&lt;5 million years</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Width:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Up to 2 km wide</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Marsquake Source:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">90% of InSight detections</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Key Discovery:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Active magmatic processes</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Geological Formation Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Geological Formation and Structure
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The Cerberus Fossae system formed through extensional tectonics, where 
        the Martian crust stretched and fractured due to underlying magmatic 
        processes. These parallel grabens (down-dropped blocks) create a distinctive 
        pattern visible from orbit, with individual fossae ranging from hundreds 
        of meters to several kilometers in width.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Formation Mechanism</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Tectonic extension driven by magma intrusion creates parallel 
            fractures as the crust pulls apart. This process is ongoing, 
            with seismic evidence suggesting continued magmatic activity 
            at depths of 30-50 kilometers beneath the surface.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Volcanic Features</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Recent pyroclastic deposits less than 250,000 years old indicate 
            explosive volcanic activity. Dark dust deposits suggest even 
            more recent volcanism, possibly within the last 50,000 years.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- InSight Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Revolutionary InSight Discoveries
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900/50 to-red-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-red-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Marsquake Epicenter (2022-2024)
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          InSight's seismometer detected 1,319 marsquakes during its mission, 
          with over 90% originating from Cerberus Fossae. This concentration 
          of seismic activity was unprecedented and revealed that Mars is 
          far more geologically active than previously thought.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The strongest marsquakes reached magnitudes of 4.7, releasing 
          significant seismic energy equivalent to 1.4–5.6 × 10¹⁵ N·m per year, 
          representing at least half of Mars' total planetary seismicity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-900/50 to-orange-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-orange-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Active Magmatic Processes
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Low-frequency marsquakes suggest a structurally weak, potentially 
          warm source region consistent with molten lava or magma at depth. 
          This challenges the long-held belief that Mars is volcanically dormant.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Spectral analysis indicates magmatic activity occurring at 40-kilometer 
          depths, with the graben system continuing to actively open and extend, 
          driven by ongoing subsurface processes.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Seismic Monitoring Breakthrough
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The concentration of seismic activity at Cerberus Fossae was initially 
        surprising to scientists who expected more distributed seismicity across 
        Mars. Instead, they discovered that most Martian surface faults are 
        not seismically active, with activity focused on this single population 
        of tectonic structures.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        This finding has revolutionized understanding of Martian tectonics, 
        suggesting that active geological processes are more localized but 
        more intense than previously modeled, with implications for understanding 
        Mars' thermal evolution and interior dynamics.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Recent Volcanic Activity Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Evidence of Recent Volcanic Activity
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Geological evidence suggests that Cerberus Fossae has experienced 
          volcanic activity much more recently than most of Mars. Dark-toned 
          deposits and fresh-appearing lava flows indicate volcanism may have 
          occurred within the past 50,000 years—extremely recent in geological terms.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Pyroclastic Deposits
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Evidence of explosive volcanism less than 250,000 years old, 
              including volcanic ash deposits in the central fossae region.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Lava Flow Evidence
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Fresh-appearing basaltic flows with minimal crater density, 
              suggesting emplacement within the last few million years.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Dark Surface Deposits
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Distinctive dark-toned materials possibly related to very 
              recent volcanic activity, within the last 50,000 years.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Volcanic Timeline
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Formation:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">&lt;5 Myr ago</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Pyroclastic:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">&lt;250 kyr ago</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Recent flows:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">&lt;50 kyr ago</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Marsquakes:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Ongoing</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Assessment Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-yellow-900/30 to-orange-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-yellow-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-yellow-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">5</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Moderate Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-yellow-300">
            Active geology with significant challenges
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Active geological processes indicate thermal energy</li>
            <li>• Recent volcanic activity suggests accessible magma</li>
            <li>• Potential geothermal energy resources</li>
            <li>• Fresh volcanic materials for construction</li>
            <li>• Ongoing outgassing could contribute to atmosphere</li>
            <li>• Well-studied seismic activity for planning</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• High seismic risk from ongoing marsquakes</li>
            <li>• Potential for future volcanic eruptions</li>
            <li>• Geological instability complicates construction</li>
            <li>• Limited surface water resources</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation in fracture systems</li>
            <li>• Unpredictable future activity patterns</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Significance
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Martian Seismology Revolution
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Cerberus Fossae has fundamentally changed our understanding of Mars' 
          interior structure and dynamics. The concentration of seismic activity 
          here has provided unprecedented insights into the planet's crustal 
          structure, thermal state, and ongoing geological processes, establishing 
          Mars as a seismically active world.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Active Planet Paradigm
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The discovery of ongoing magmatic activity challenges the traditional 
          view of Mars as a geologically dead planet. Evidence for recent volcanism 
          and active magma chambers suggests Mars remains thermally active, with 
          implications for understanding planetary evolution and the potential 
          for ongoing atmosphere modification through volcanic outgassing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Potential
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        As one of Mars' most geologically active regions, Cerberus Fossae 
        presents both unique opportunities and challenges for future exploration. 
        The ongoing seismic activity and evidence of recent volcanism make it 
        a priority target for understanding Mars' current state and future evolution.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Research Priorities
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Direct sampling of recent volcanic deposits</li>
            <li>• Continuous seismic monitoring network</li>
            <li>• Subsurface magma chamber detection</li>
            <li>• Gas emission monitoring and analysis</li>
            <li>• Thermal mapping of active regions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Engineering Considerations
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Seismic-resistant infrastructure design</li>
            <li>• Real-time hazard monitoring systems</li>
            <li>• Geothermal energy exploitation potential</li>
            <li>• Safe distance protocols for settlements</li>
            <li>• Emergency response planning</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/insight/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              InSight Mars Mission
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/edu/resources/teachable-moment/how-insight-revealed-the-heart-of-mars/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              How InSight Revealed Mars' Interior
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41550-022-01803-y"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Tectonics of Cerberus Fossae (Nature, 2022)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1029/2021JE007118"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Marsquake Properties Study (AGU, 2022)
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>